The Todoist Monthly

=E2=80=8A

All that=E2=80=99s new in the Todoist-verse =E2=80=93 August 2025

---------------------------------------------------------------------------=
-----

=E2=80=8A

Hey! It=E2=80=99s
[https://res.cloudinary.com/imagist/image/fetch/f_png/c_scale,h_48,w_48/r_m=
ax/https://images.ctfassets.net/5zyjowl7hbbz/5TLvxjz8HyhoGtse9WAVau/8f7a80d=
84cd6348e87310e4444ed9f46/Denise_Avatar.jpeg?_a=3DDATAg1JsZAA0]
Denise from Todoist. =F0=9F=91=8B

=E2=80=8A

August has this funny way of making everything feel like a fresh start, doe=
sn=E2=80=99t
it?

=E2=80=8A

You=E2=80=99re back from vacation (or watching everyone else return from th=
eirs), and
there=E2=80=99s this renewed energy in the air. September=E2=80=99s around =
the corner, Q4 is
approaching fast, and suddenly you=E2=80=99re thinking: =E2=80=9COkay, how =
am I actually going
to make this all happen?=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=8A

Whether you=E2=80=99re coordinating with colleagues on year-end priorities =
or just
trying to get your own momentum back, this month let=E2=80=99s focus on the=
 basics =E2=80=93
they tend to make things feel less intense.

=E2=80=8A

Back to basics: The power of simple systems

=E2=80=8A

When life gets busy, these three simple principles matter more than any
elaborate setup:

=E2=80=8A

Build a structure that makes sense to you. Set up projects in a way that mi=
rrors
how you naturally think about work and life =E2=80=93 whether that=E2=80=99=
s =E2=80=9CWork/Personal/Side
Projects,=E2=80=9D per-client setups, or goal-driven buckets like =E2=80=9C=
Q4 Sales Targets.=E2=80=9D
=F0=9F=92=A1When your Todoist reflects how you naturally think about your
responsibilities, everything falls into place.

=E2=80=8A

[https://todoist.doist-emails.com/_next/static/images/lightbulb-yellow_6f87=
d099bc73d60aa043989251b3a548.png]

Team tip: If you have a team workspace, you can also use folders to organiz=
e
your team projects
[https://www.todoist.com/help/articles/use-folders-to-organize-team-project=
s-uoElGQdbb?utm_source=3Dtodoist&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_campaign=3D2025_08_=
todoist_monthly].
Plus, folders sync to all your team members=E2=80=99 accounts, meaning ever=
yone sees the
same organized structure.

=E2=80=8A

Automate the routine stuff. Weekly carpool duties, monthly inventory checks=
,
annual contract renewals =E2=80=93 anything that repeats should be a recurr=
ing task. One
setup, zero brain space wasted.

=E2=80=8A

Use templates for repeated processes. Back-to-school prep, new client
onboarding, monthly payroll processing =E2=80=93 any multi-step process tha=
t happens
more than once gets turned into a reusable template. You=E2=80=99ll never r=
einvent the
wheel (or miss a step). Here=E2=80=99s how you create a template
[https://www.todoist.com/help/articles/introduction-to-templates-uofJ8i40M?=
utm_source=3Dtodoist&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_campaign=3D2025_08_todoist_mont=
hly].

=E2=80=8A

What=E2=80=99s new this month

=E2=80=8A

Enhanced quick access on desktop =E2=80=93 See today=E2=80=99s and tomorrow=
=E2=80=99s tasks + calendar
events straight from your tray menu. Jump into work without opening the ful=
l
app. Click a task to get to it, or click an event to open it in your browse=
r.
Perfect for those quick check-ins between meetings.

=E2=80=8A
[https://images.ctfassets.net/5zyjowl7hbbz/5nWLcrMo3EvaPTq1UPVZYt/45f0bd327=
df3f24414b2ba3d47c8d76d/enhanced-tray-menu.png?w=3D1000&fm=3Dpng]

=E2=80=8A

Visual recurring scheduler =E2=80=93 Setting recurring tasks with natural l=
anguage
usually works like a breeze, but complex patterns like =E2=80=9Cevery three=
 weeks on
Thursday until Oct 31=E2=80=9D can be tricky. The new visual interface take=
s away the
guesswork =E2=80=93 just set it visually.

=E2=80=8A
[https://images.ctfassets.net/5zyjowl7hbbz/1lPo93ew7SwowsMLxBdndD/63d82f9ee=
65b0e11276e13bd6433dce5/new-recurring-scheduler.png?w=3D1000&fm=3Dpng]

=E2=80=8A

Real simplicity in action

=E2=80=8A

Twelve years ago,
[https://res.cloudinary.com/imagist/image/fetch/f_png/c_scale,h_48,w_48/r_m=
ax/https://images.ctfassets.net/5zyjowl7hbbz/C2rjNcUfrTjc2LoQThRbc/8ee21be5=
f4ac9e556987d6e7d73f0c41/Frank-Bravo.jpeg?_a=3DDATAg1JsZAA0]
Frank Bravo, CTO at Embarcadero Media, was drowning in systems so complex t=
hat
it took more time managing the workflow than doing actual work.

=E2=80=8A

He ditched the chaos, switched to Todoist, and completely rethought how he
approached productivity =E2=80=93 both personally and with his team.

=E2=80=8A

The team built an elegantly simple workflow: emails from their ticketing sy=
stem
automatically become Todoist tasks for the assigned team member. Recurring
maintenance tasks, individual projects, and customer support tickets all fl=
ow
into one unified system.

=E2=80=8A

Today, Frank and his team live by one ironclad rule: =E2=80=9CIf it=E2=80=
=99s not in Todoist, it
doesn=E2=80=99t exist.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=8A

Read Frank=E2=80=99s full story
[https://todoist.com/inspiration/how-a-cto-simplified-his-teams-workflow?ut=
m_source=3Dtodoist&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_campaign=3D2025_08_todoist_monthl=
y]
=E2=86=92

=E2=80=8A
[https://images.ctfassets.net/5zyjowl7hbbz/hKTNihsNuMyzmowvPBDmJ/34a5e644ec=
622541da9045bf5b0d937a/Case-Study-Frank-Bravo.png?w=3D1000&fm=3Dpng]https:/=
/todoist.com/inspiration/how-a-cto-simplified-his-teams-workflow?utm_source=
=3Dtodoist&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_campaign=3D2025_08_todoist_monthly

=E2=80=8A

Frank=E2=80=99s recommendations for staying organized

=E2=80=8A

After a solid decade of working in Todoist every day, Frank offers three
practical tips:

=E2=80=8A

 1. Create your projects =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=80=99t have good =
organization, it=E2=80=99s gonna be
    just a junk drawer of tasks.=E2=80=9D

 2. Leverage labels =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CUse labels to track status and categ=
orize your work.=E2=80=9D

 3. Use the calendar integration =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CConnect your calendar s=
o you can assign
    things to days and times.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=8A

When simple starts to feel messy

=E2=80=8A

Many of you already use Todoist with others =E2=80=93 perhaps even share pr=
ojects with
people from work.

=E2=80=8A

But multiple shared projects are starting to encroach on your personal spac=
e, or
your colleague=E2=80=99s project naming approach is ... different (how many=
 emojis does
one project need?). What used to feel clean now feels cluttered.

=E2=80=8A

That=E2=80=99s where team workspaces help: a dedicated space that keeps per=
sonal and
shared projects separate, with zero extra complexity. Same Todoist principl=
es,
just applied to teamwork.

=E2=80=8A

See how team workspaces work
[https://www.todoist.com/teamwork?utm_source=3Dtodoist&utm_medium=3Demail&u=
tm_campaign=3D2025_08_todoist_monthly]
=E2=86=92

=E2=80=8A

---------------------------------------------------------------------------=
-----

=E2=80=8A

Complexity is the last thing you need when you=E2=80=99re trying to rebuild=
 momentum.
Step back, ask what=E2=80=99s working, and let the rest go. The answer is u=
sually
simpler than we think.

=E2=80=8A

Here=E2=80=99s to a bit of housekeeping.

